Related to COMA-2505 and in an effort to improve sync performance, the client application(s) need to be able to FIRST fetch a list of Groups and UserGroups for a given user so that individual "sync per group" can occur.

We _could_ just stick this method in /v1/sync or /v1/user controllers but we may want to start thinking ahead to what the API structure might look like if we had an 'online-only' version of the app vs the current 'offline' version. The online-only version of the API would need to have endpoints for all the different types of entities /groups, /mice, /labels, /cages, etc. This will take quite a bit more thought because we will likely have to include search query parameters to most of these endpoints, sort parameters, paging, etc.

The endpoints could go anywhere but my suggestion is this:

* (PRIMARY Importance) New API endpoint (GET /v1/groups)
** Returns an array of the same GroupDTO object we currently get as part of the /v1/sync/GetSyncPayload method call.
** This is ALL Groups the current user is a member of. No filtering whatsoever. Even include soft-deleted (dateDeleted != nil)
** Example response, shortened for brevity: 
{code:json}
{ "groups" : [ { "groupId" : "FFF...", "name" : "Sandbox", "enrollmentKey" : "SANDBOX"}] }
{code}
* (SECONDARY Importance) New API endpoint (GET /v1/groups/userGroups or possibly /v1/userGroups or /v1/userGroups/associated)
** The rational for /v1/groups/userGroups is that it would imply ALL Groups and ALL those Groups' users (which is what we want).
** Returns an array of the same UserGroupDTO object we currently get as part of the /v1/sync/GetSyncPayload method call.
** This is ALL UserGroups "associated" with the user the logged in user, not just the ones where "userId == currentUser.userId". Even include soft-deleted (dateDeleted != nil)
*** This means that if the current user is part of 2 groups (A and B) and 'Group A' has 25 users and 'Group B' has 50 users, that the response to this API call will include 75 UserGroup records.
** Example response, shortened for brevity: 
{code:json}
{ "userGroups" : [ { "userGroupId" : "FFF...", "groupId" : "FEF...", "userId" : "ABC..."}] }
{code}

