column157:
04/Nov/17 9:36 PM;rwilliams;From Jim to Nate (10/25/2017)

For testing and finalizing some portions of the development, we have these questions:

For multiple WT strains:
Jim: We narrowed down that only 2 of the mutation probes can ever be positive.
{color:#59afe1}Nate: Yes{color}

Jim: If the first mutation probe is positive and the second mutation probe is negative, the second WT probe must be positive. With this information we can continue to build the matrix for multiple WTs on the same strain.
{color:#59afe1}Nate: Maybe? Might be better to state that in this case if any mutant probe is negative then it’s wildtype probe must be positive. (if Mut1 is negative then WT1 must be positive). There are more rules and I feel like there must be a system. We can discuss further and try to figure it out.{color}

Jim: Is there a limit to the number of mutations on the same gene when genotyping with our service?
{color:#59afe1}Nate: Technically, no. (You can add as many probes in OM as you like and OM has no idea about genes). However, realistically I doubt we see more than 2-3 mutations on a given gene on a mouse/sample{color}

Jim: If we have multiple WTs on a strain with multiple mutations, is there a scenario where 1 of the mutations would have a SNP probe selected?
{color:#59afe1}Nate: Yes{color}

For SNP probes: 
Jim: Would a SNP probe ever be used for a transgene?
{color:#59afe1}Nate: We currently do this for a very few customers after we desperately try to talk them out of it. I think it is ok to not allow this in Colony (at least at first){color}
Jim: If a user selects a SNP probe for a link to a mutation, do they then NOT need to also select the WT probe? 
